results.title: Reclining Sandstone Buddha: Sri Lanka
results.description:
This reclining Buddha is located in the city of Polonnaruwa, a medieval capital and World Heritage Site in Sri Lanka. 

This beautiful piece of sculpture is a symbol of what is possible when we meet suffering with insight and compassion. In a moment of difficulty, being able to say: This is really hard. This hurts. Everyone has hard experiences at some time or another. Pain, disappointment, and loss touch every human life. May I be kind to myself, especially in moments of difficulty.

results.title: Karuna: Compassion
results.description:
This image was photographed at the Borobudur Temple in Java, Indonesia. Borobudur was built in the 9th Century and under ash for over 1000 years following the eruption of a volcano. It was rediscovered in the early 1800’s and renovated in 1983. 

Compassion is a response to a deep knowing of suffering There is an empathy here – a being able to feel, be honest about, and support awareness of our own pain, and from that, another’s pain. Compassion is not sympathy. It is an inside job.

results.title: Red Sole Man
results.description:
This photograph was taken in the neighborhood of Getsemani, just outside the Old Walled Town of Cartagena, Columbia.

This neighborhood is known for its murals and street art.  I was struck by the contrasting states of mind in the mural and the red sole man, sitting in the street, appearing unable to smile as the word, ‘sonrie’ was suggesting.

results.title: Metta: Loving Kindness
results.description:
This image was photographed at the Borobudur Temple in Java, Indonesia.  Borobudur was built in the 9th Century and under ash for over 1,000 years following the eruption of a volcano.  It was rediscovered in the early 1800’s and renovated in 1983.

It is the largest Buddhist temple in the world.  The journey through Borobudur follows a path around the monument and ascends to the top through symbolic levels of the world of desire; the world of compassion; and the world of formlessness.

results.title: Camelback
results.description:
Can you guess what this image is? Take a moment and look deeply. What do you see? The title of this photograph is 'Camelback'. Maybe this gives you a strong hint.

It is actually the body of a camel whose hair was shaved to reveal this artistic design. At the Nagaur Camel Festival, held annually (like a car show) in Rajasthan, India, camels win prizes for a variety of things, including beauty.

results.title: Orange Doorway
results.description:
This doorway was photographed in Northern India, near Jodhpur.  The image invites us to Pause, Observe, and Open to those doorways and openings within our own life that lead us into deeper contact and connection with our self and others.

When we can stand at the doorway of our own direct experience and learn to be our self, just as we are, our heart opens to peace, to compassion, to growing acceptance.  We enter each moment, just as it is, meeting what’s here with kind awareness, curious attention, while learning to say…’This moment is like this…’

results.title: Kasuga Taisha Shrine: Nara
results.description:
Kasuga Taisha is considered Nara’s most celebrated shrine. Nara was the first capital of Japan, and is located between Kyoto and Osaka. Due to its historical past, Nara remains full of treasures, including some of Japan’s oldest and largest temples. 

This Shrine is famous for its lanterns, which have been donated by worshipers. Many stone lanterns light the path to sacred spaces. 

The carving on the lanterns in this photograph means ‘Kasuga Shrine.’

results.title: No Mud, No Lotus
results.description:
The lotus flower is a powerful symbol of transformation. Without muddy, soiled, murky waters, a lotus flower would not bloom. Its roots grow from conditions that are soiled and not pure. 

Similarly, the places in each of us that look or feel ‘soiled’ or imperfect can be a breeding ground for beauty, compassion, and wisdom to grow. 

This photograph was taken from a carved door in Bhutan, a small country located entirely within the Himalaya mountain range. It is known for its attention to the importance of ‘gross national happiness’ used to measure the collective happiness in a nation.

results.title: Moss Temple: Kyoto, Japan
results.description:
This photo was taken at the Moss Temple, which is famed for its moss garden, and one of Kyoto’s World Heritage Sites. 

The gardens were designed in 1339 by Muso Soseki, a Zen Buddhist monk and teacher, who was also known during his lifetime as a calligrapher and poet. Approximately 120 varieties of moss grow inside the temple’s grounds. 

The garden is divided into upper and lower sections. The upper section is a dry landscape garden. The lower section (where this photograph was taken), features paths around a pond. 

Walking the grounds here invites a meditative attitude where the senses open and are nurtured, simply in being present.

results.title: Reclining Buddha
results.description:
Believe it or not, I took this photograph in a relatively dark cave in Dambulla, Sri Lanka, which had been treasured by many kings since the 1st Century, B.C.  

I held my breath to steady my camera and take this photograph, fascinated by its antiquity, and mesmerized by its radiance and beauty.

The Buddha taught there are 4 different formal postures for meditating:  sitting, standing, walking, and lying down.  What matters most is not about posture, but cultivating a restful and alert attitude.  We observe whatever is present at each of the sense doors:  light for the eye; sound waves for the ear; odors for the nose; tastes for the tongue; a sensation in the body; a thought or feeling arising.  Consciousness becomes a stream of watching things come and go without getting hijacked by specific desires, aversions, or delusions.

results.title: Eyes of Buddha
results.description:
This is a monument at the Lhakhang Nunnery in Punakha, Bhutan.  The eyes of the Buddha invite us to awaken to insight, wisdom, and compassion.  Wisdom may have a range of meanings, but the wisdom of the Buddha is fairly specific.  When he began his own exploration, he asked:  Why do we suffer and is it possible to be free?

What we see is what we get.  Given our habits of mind and less recognized biases and fears, we often don’t see things as they are.  We see things as we are.

results.title: Paro Pilgrim
results.description:
Pilgrims make a spiritual journey, often covering hundreds of miles to the annual Paro festival.  After every 8 steps, a person does a series of prostrations aimed at purifying their mind and heart in preparation for their arrival at the holy site.

This female pilgrim was walking along a highway on her way to Paro.  She wears both gloves and an apron to protect her body on the hard surface of the road in order to do her prostrations.

results.title: Papua New Guinea Tribal Mask: Spirit House, Sepik River
results.description:
Travels Through Humanity is the name
of my growing body of photographic work,
taken in remote places throughout the world.

This work embraces the human landscape of
diversity while also highlighting that which
is essentially human – our need for connection,
a quest for safety and sense of belonging, and
our innate desire to be seen and accepted deeply.

I hope in my work to convey this sense of ‘seeing,’
and in so doing, help the viewer to see the many
faces and facets of our shared humanity.

results.title: Mother Tree: Sulawesi, Indonesia
results.description:
Deep in the jungles of Tana Tonaja on the Island of Sulawesi, Indonesia, a Banyon tree serves as a grave for babies who died before they reach six months of age.  The compartments in the tree hold the small deceased baby.  The baby becomes one with the tree.  

It is as if the grieving parents turn their baby over to the care and protection of the greatest mother of all, Mother Earth.  Here their baby rests with the other deceased babies, reminding the parents that they are not alone in their grief.

results.title: Yellow-Faced Huli Man: Papua New Guinea
results.description:
This man is from the Huli tribe in Papua New Guinea where the men like to wear make-up, especially when they perform tribal dances.  He wears a headdress that is made from human hair and decorated with feathers from the spectacular bird of paradise.  

When I travel to these far-away places, within myself or out in the world, I am returning to the quintessential question again and again of ‘who are you really’ beyond the face and beneath the physical appearance.  These inner and outer places carry a potential to feel and be felt by each other.

results.title: Mursi Mother With Baby: Omo River Valley, Ethiopia
results.description:
The Mursi tribal women, who live among 8000 people in a remote area of Mago National Park in southwestern Ethiopia, pierce their lower lip in their early 20’s  and progressively stretch it over the course of a year’s time.  The women make the lip plates from clay, and color them with ochre and charcoal until the lip plates are baked in a fire.

The size of a woman’s lip plate will determine the bride price.  A large plate may bring 50 head of cattle to this woman and her family.  The lip plate also acts as a protection for the woman’s safety in being identified as a Mursi woman and remaining close to home, with her tribe.  

This Mursi mother was proud to show me her lip plate and to pose with her baby, who was also adorned with decorative body paint.  The cloud that drifted above her head as I took this photograph looked and felt like a magical touch.

results.title: Huli Warrior: Papua New Guinea
results.description:
The Huli tribal men in Papua New Guinea are some of the most decorative men in the world.  During the annual Sing Sing festival in the Western Highlands of Mount Hagan, these men paint their faces like the bird of paradise.  

With these painted faces, it is believed that the men transcend the human realm and embody the realm of the plant and animal realm as well.  These men shared a willingness to be seen, as they are, with few if any barriers.

results.title: Hamar Rainbow Woman: Ethiopia, Africa
results.description:
I took this photograph at an outdoor market in Southern Ethiopia where this woman was selling a few spices displayed on a small cloth.  She appeared both surprised and receptive to my presence and request to photograph her.  

Hamar tribal women are known for their unusual hair styles that are shaped with a mixture of butter and ocher.

Often the Hamar women are decorated with cowrie shells and when married, wear a tight fitting ornament around their neck until the end of their life.   

I felt delighted with the light that came through both her umbrella and our momentary connection.
